rb5ref_en_5_debugmode.html§DEBUGMODE§DEBUGMODE mode§Sets the integrated RapidBATCH script-debugger to one of the three debug-modes. Possible parameter values are STEP for stepwise debugging, TRACE for trace-debugging, and NONE to switch the debugger off.<!-- br --><br><!-- br --><br><!-- br -->Using this method, the debugger can be started directly in the script, e.g. at a critical position.<!-- br --><!-- br --><br /><!-- br --><img style="padding-top: 30px;" src="img/debug_step.gif" alt="RapidBATCH Debugger in Step-Mode" title="Screenshot" />§echo <font color="#0000ff">'A debug test...'</font><br /><!-- br --><br /><!-- br --><font color="#808080">rem Start debugger</font><br /><!-- br -->debugmode step<br /><!-- br --><br /><!-- br --><font color="#808080">rem Let's execute the next instructon...</font><br /><!-- br -->echo <font color="#0000ff">'Hello World'</font><br /><!-- br --><b>end</b><!-- br -->§This statement is only included in the script-interpreter provided with RapidBATCH Professional Edition.<br><!-- br -->DEBUGMODE is ignored by the compiler and is not provided in compiled scripts.<br><br><!-- br --><!-- br -->You can also start the debugger by setting the environment variable RB_DEBUGMODE to one of the desired values BEFORE the RapidBATCH-script is executed.<!-- br -->
rb5ref_en_5_debugvars.html§DEBUGVARS§DEBUGVARS var1,var2,var3 ... var<sup/>n</sup><br /><!-- br -->DEBUGVARS mode§Inserts the variables that are passed at DEBUGVARS into the debug-dialog window, to observe and modify them. All desired variables that sould be watched need to be separated by commas. Instead of specifying a variable-list, the values AUTO and NONE can be specified. AUTO does automatically insert all newly declared variables into the debug-dialog, NONE switches this option off again.<!-- br --><!-- br --><br /><!-- br --><img style="padding-top: 30px;" src="img/debug_vars.gif" alt="RapidBATCH Debugger with watched variables in Step-Mode" title="Screenshot" />§debugmode step<br /><!-- br --><font color="#808080">rem watch [a] and [b] only</font><br /><!-- br -->debugvars <font color="#000080">[a]</font>, <font color="#000080">[b]</font><br /><!-- br --><font color="#000080">[a]</font> = <font color="#0000ff">'12'</font><br /><!-- br --><font color="#000080">[b]</font> = <font color="#000080">[a]</font> * <font color="#0000ff">'2'</font><br /><!-- br --><font color="#000080">[c]</font> = <font color="#000080">[a]</font> * <font color="#000080">[b]</font><br /><!-- br --><br /><!-- br --><font color="#808080">rem now, add all new variables automatically</font><br /><!-- br -->debugvars auto<br /><!-- br --><br /><!-- br --><font color="#000080">[new]</font> = <font color="#0000ff">'New value'</font><br /><!-- br -->echo <font color="#000080">[new]</font><!-- br -->§This statement is only included in the script-interpreter provided with RapidBATCH Professional Edition.<br><!-- br -->DEBUGVARS is ignored by the compiler and is not provided in compiled scripts.<br><br><!-- br --><!-- br -->Set the environment-variable RB_DEBUGVARS to one of the possible parameters before the script is executed to set these variables by default.
